    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my blueberry bushes are starting to look kinda weird. the leaves are turning yellow but the veins are still green. i cant tell if i need more nitrogen or if the soil is just too alkaline for them. any idea what's going on?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "This symptom, known as interveinal chlorosis, often indicates a nutrient deficiency or soil issue. Since the veins remain green, it strongly suggests a problem with the uptake of mobile nutrients, most commonly iron or manganese, which are sensitive to high soil pH. Testing your soil's pH is the best first step to determine if alkalinity is locking up these essential minerals for your blueberries. Adjusting the acidity, perhaps with elemental sulfur or sulfur-coated fertilizer, should help resolve this.",
      "source": "target",
